{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"The north coast of California has rainforests --"},{"time":5000,"text":"temperate rainforests -- where it can rain more than 100 inches a year."},{"time":10000,"text":"This is the realm of the Coast Redwood tree."},{"time":14000,"text":"Its species name is Sequoia sempervirens."},{"time":17000,"text":"Sequoia sempervirens is the tallest living organism on Earth."},{"time":21000,"text":"The range of the species goes up to as much as 380 feet tall."},{"time":26000,"text":"That's 38 stories tall."},{"time":28000,"text":"These are trees that would stand out in midtown Manhattan."},{"time":32000,"text":"Nobody knows how old the oldest living Coast Redwoods are"},{"time":36000,"text":"because nobody has ever drilled into any of them"},{"time":38000,"text":"to count their annual growth rings, and, in any case,"},{"time":41000,"text":"the centers of the oldest individuals appear to be hollow."},{"time":45000,"text":"But it's believed that the oldest living Redwoods"},{"time":48000,"text":"are perhaps 2,500 years old -- roughly the age of the Parthenon --"},{"time":54000,"text":"although it's also suspected that there may be individual trees"},{"time":57000,"text":"that are older than that."}]},{"cues":[{"time":59000,"text":"You can see the range of the Coast Redwoods. It's here, in red."},{"time":63000,"text":"The largest individuals of this species,"},{"time":65000,"text":"the dreadnoughts of their kind, live just on the north coast of California,"},{"time":70000,"text":"where the rain is really intense."},{"time":73000,"text":"In recent historic times, about 96 percent of the Coast Redwood forest"},{"time":79000,"text":"was cut down, especially in a series of bursts of intense liquidation logging,"},{"time":86000,"text":"clear-cutting that took place in the 1970s through the early 1990s."},{"time":92000,"text":"Even so, about four percent of the primeval Redwood rainforest remains intact,"},{"time":100000,"text":"wild and now protected -- entirely protected --"},{"time":104000,"text":"in a chain of small parks strung out like pearls"},{"time":107000,"text":"along the north coast of California, including Redwood National Park."},{"time":111000,"text":"But curiously, Redwood rainforests, the fragments that we have left,"},{"time":116000,"text":"to this day remain under-explored."},{"time":119000,"text":"Redwood rainforest is incredibly difficult to move through,"},{"time":124000,"text":"and even today, individual trees are being discovered"},{"time":127000,"text":"that have never been seen before, including, in the summer of 2006,"},{"time":131000,"text":"Hyperion, the world's tallest tree."}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"I'm going to do a little Gedanken experiment."},{"time":137000,"text":"I'm going to ask you to imagine what a Redwood really is as a living organism."},{"time":141000,"text":"And, Chris, if I could have you up here? I have a tape measure."},{"time":149000,"text":"It's a kind loaner from TED."},{"time":151000,"text":"And Chris, if you could take the end of that tape measure?"},{"time":155000,"text":"We're going to show you what the diameter"},{"time":157000,"text":"at breast height of a big Redwood is."},{"time":160000,"text":"Unfortunately, this tape isn't long enough -- it's only a 25-foot tape."},{"time":169000,"text":"Chris, could you extend your arm out that way? There we go. OK."},{"time":174000,"text":"And maybe about here, about 30 feet, is the diameter of a big Redwood."},{"time":182000,"text":"Now, let your imagination go upward into space."},{"time":185000,"text":"Think about this tree, rising upward into Redwood space, 325 feet,"},{"time":195000,"text":"32 stories, an individual living organism articulating its forms"},{"time":200000,"text":"upward into space over long periods of time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":204000,"text":"The Redwood species seems to exist in another kind of time:"},{"time":209000,"text":"not human time, but what we might call Redwood time."},{"time":213000,"text":"Redwood time moves at a more stately pace than human time."},{"time":218000,"text":"To us, when we look at a Redwood tree, it seems to be motionless and still,"},{"time":223000,"text":"and yet Redwoods are constantly in motion,"},{"time":226000,"text":"moving upward into space, articulating themselves"},{"time":231000,"text":"and filling Redwood space over Redwood time, over thousands of years."},{"time":236000,"text":"Plant this small seed, wait 2,000 years, and you get this:"},{"time":240000,"text":"the Lost Monarch."},{"time":242000,"text":"It dwells in the Grove of Titans on the north coast,"},{"time":244000,"text":"and was discovered in 1998."},{"time":247000,"text":"And yet, when you look at the base of a Redwood tree,"},{"time":249000,"text":"you're not seeing the organism."},{"time":251000,"text":"You're like a mouse looking at the foot of an elephant,"},{"time":254000,"text":"and most of the organism is overhead, unseen."}]},{"cues":[{"time":257000,"text":"I became very interested, and I wrote about a couple."},{"time":261000,"text":"Steve Sillett and Marie Antoine are the principal explorers"},{"time":264000,"text":"of the Redwood forest canopy. They're world-class athletes,"},{"time":267000,"text":"and they also are world-class forest ecology scientists."},{"time":273000,"text":"Steve Sillett, when he was a 19-year-old college student"},{"time":276000,"text":"at Reed College, had heard that the Redwood forest canopy"},{"time":280000,"text":"is considered to be a so-called Redwood desert."},{"time":283000,"text":"That is to say, at that time it was believed"},{"time":285000,"text":"that there was nothing up there except the branches of Redwood trees."},{"time":289000,"text":"And with a friend of his, he took it upon himself to free-climb a Redwood"},{"time":292000,"text":"without ropes or any equipment to see what was up there."},{"time":295000,"text":"He climbed up a small tree next to this giant Redwood,"},{"time":298000,"text":"and then he leaped through space and grabbed a branch with his hands,"},{"time":304000,"text":"and ended up hanging, like catching a bar of a trapeze."},{"time":307000,"text":"And then, from there, he climbed directly up the bark"},{"time":310000,"text":"until he got to the top of the tree."}]},{"cues":[{"time":312000,"text":"His friend, a guy named Marwood Harris, was following behind."},{"time":316000,"text":"Neither one of them had noticed that there was"},{"time":318000,"text":"a Yellow Jacket wasp's nest the size of a bowling ball"},{"time":322000,"text":"hanging from the branch that Steve had jumped into."},{"time":324000,"text":"And when Marwood made the jump, he was covered with wasps"},{"time":328000,"text":"stinging him in the face and eyes. He nearly let go."},{"time":332000,"text":"He would have fallen to his death, being 75 feet above the ground."},{"time":335000,"text":"But they made it to the top, and what they found"},{"time":337000,"text":"was not a Redwood desert, but a lost world --"},{"time":340000,"text":"a kind of three-dimensional labyrinth in the air, filled with unknown life."},{"time":344000,"text":"Now, I had been working on other topics:"},{"time":348000,"text":"the emergence of infectious diseases,"},{"time":351000,"text":"which come out of the natural ecosystems of the Earth,"},{"time":354000,"text":"make a trans-species jump, and get into humans."}]},{"cues":[{"time":357000,"text":"After three books on this, it got to be a bit much, in a way."},{"time":361000,"text":"My wife and I adore our children."},{"time":364000,"text":"And I began climbing trees with my kids as just something to do with them,"},{"time":369000,"text":"using the so-called arborist climbing technique,"},{"time":372000,"text":"with ropes. You use ropes to get yourself up into the crown of a tree."},{"time":376000,"text":"Children are incredibly adept at climbing trees."},{"time":379000,"text":"That's my son, Oliver."},{"time":381000,"text":"They don't seem to suffer from the same fear of heights that humans do."}]},{"cues":[{"time":385000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":389000,"text":"If ontogeny recapitulates phylogeny, then children"},{"time":393000,"text":"are somewhat closer to our roots as primates in the arboreal forest."},{"time":398000,"text":"Humans appear to be the only primates that I know of"},{"time":402000,"text":"that are afraid of heights."},{"time":404000,"text":"All other primates, when they're scared,"},{"time":406000,"text":"they run up a tree, where they feel safe."},{"time":409000,"text":"We camped overnight in the trees, in tree boats."},{"time":413000,"text":"This is my daughter Laura, then 15, looking out of a tree boat."},{"time":416000,"text":"She's, by the way, tied in with a rope so she can't fall."},{"time":421000,"text":"Looking out of a tree boat in the morning and hearing birdsong"},{"time":424000,"text":"coming in three dimensions around us."},{"time":426000,"text":"We had been visited in the night by flying squirrels,"},{"time":429000,"text":"who don't seem to recognize humans for what they are"},{"time":432000,"text":"because they've never seen them in the canopy before."},{"time":434000,"text":"And we practiced advanced techniques like sky-walking,"},{"time":437000,"text":"where you can move from tree to tree through space,"},{"time":440000,"text":"rather like Spiderman."},{"time":442000,"text":"It became a writing project."}]},{"cues":[{"time":444000,"text":"When Steve Sillett gets up into a big Redwood, he fires an arrow,"},{"time":448000,"text":"which trails a fishing line, which gets over a branch in the tree,"},{"time":451000,"text":"and then you ascend up a rope which has been dragged into the tree by the line."},{"time":455000,"text":"You ascend 30 stories."},{"time":457000,"text":"There are two people climbing this tree, Gaya,"},{"time":460000,"text":"which is thought to be one of the oldest Redwoods. There they are."},{"time":463000,"text":"They are only one-seventh of the way up that tree."},{"time":467000,"text":"You do feel a sense of exposure."},{"time":469000,"text":"There is a small person right down there on the ground."},{"time":472000,"text":"You feel like you're climbing a wall of wood."},{"time":474000,"text":"But then you enter the Redwood canopy,"},{"time":476000,"text":"and it's like coming through a layer of clouds."},{"time":479000,"text":"And all of a sudden, you lose sight of the ground,"},{"time":482000,"text":"and you also lose sight of the sky,"},{"time":484000,"text":"and you're in a three-dimensional labyrinth in the air"},{"time":487000,"text":"filled with hanging gardens of ferns growing out of soil,"},{"time":490000,"text":"which is populated with all kinds of small organisms."}]},{"cues":[{"time":494000,"text":"There are epiphytes, plants that grow on trees."},{"time":497000,"text":"These are huckleberry bushes."},{"time":499000,"text":"Many species of mosses, and then all sorts of lichens just plastering the tree."},{"time":505000,"text":"When you get near the top of the tree, you feel like you can't fall --"},{"time":508000,"text":"in fact, it's difficult to move."},{"time":510000,"text":"You're worming your way through branches which are crowded"},{"time":513000,"text":"with living things that don't occur near the ground."},{"time":516000,"text":"It's like scuba diving into a coral reef,"},{"time":518000,"text":"except you're going upward instead of downward."},{"time":520000,"text":"And then the trees tend to flare out into platform-like areas at the top."},{"time":524000,"text":"Maria's sitting on one of them."},{"time":526000,"text":"These limbs could be five to six hundred years old."},{"time":528000,"text":"Redwoods grow very slowly in their tops."},{"time":531000,"text":"They also have a feature: thickets of huckleberry bushes"},{"time":534000,"text":"that grow out of the tops of Redwood trees"},{"time":536000,"text":"that are technically known as huckleberry afros,"},{"time":539000,"text":"and you can sit there and snack on the berries while you're resting."}]},{"cues":[{"time":543000,"text":"Redwoods have an enormous surface area that extends upward into space"},{"time":548000,"text":"because they have a propensity to do something called reiteration."},{"time":552000,"text":"A Redwood is a fractal. And as they put out limbs,"},{"time":556000,"text":"the limbs burst into small trees, copies of the Redwood."},{"time":561000,"text":"Now, here we see a reiteration in Chronos, one of the older Redwoods."},{"time":565000,"text":"This reiteration is a huge flying buttress"},{"time":569000,"text":"that comes out the tree itself."},{"time":571000,"text":"This buttress is less than halfway up the tree."},{"time":574000,"text":"And then it bursts into a forest of Redwoods."},{"time":577000,"text":"This particular extra trunk is a meter across at the base"},{"time":582000,"text":"and extends upward for 150 feet."},{"time":584000,"text":"It's as big as any of the biggest trees east of the Mississippi River,"},{"time":588000,"text":"and yet it's only a minor feature on Chronos."}]},{"cues":[{"time":591000,"text":"This three-dimensional map of the crown structure of a Redwood named Iluvatar,"},{"time":597000,"text":"made by Steve Sillett, Marie Antoine and their colleagues, gives you an idea."},{"time":601000,"text":"What you're seeing here is a hierarchical schematic development"},{"time":605000,"text":"of the trunks of this tree as it has elaborated itself over time into six layers of fractal,"},{"time":611000,"text":"of trunks springing from trunks springing from trunks."},{"time":616000,"text":"I asked Steve to put a human being in this to give a sense of scale."},{"time":621000,"text":"There's the person, right there. The person is waving to us."},{"time":626000,"text":"I've wanted to ask Craig Venter if it would be possible to insert"},{"time":632000,"text":"a synthetic chromosome into a human"},{"time":634000,"text":"so that we could reiterate ourselves if we wanted to."},{"time":638000,"text":"And if we were able to reiterate, then the fingers of our hand"},{"time":641000,"text":"would be people who looked like us,"},{"time":645000,"text":"and they would have people on their hands and so on."},{"time":648000,"text":"And if we had Redwood-like biology,"},{"time":650000,"text":"we would have six layers of people on our hands, as it were."},{"time":654000,"text":"And it would be a lovely thing to be able to wave to someone"},{"time":656000,"text":"and have all our reiterations wave at the same time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":660000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":662000,"text":"To reiterate the point, let's go closer into Iluvatar."},{"time":668000,"text":"We're looking at that yellow box."},{"time":671000,"text":"And this hallucinatory drawing shows you --"},{"time":673000,"text":"everything you see in this drawing is Iluvatar."},{"time":677000,"text":"These are millennial structures -- portions of the tree"},{"time":680000,"text":"that are believed to be more than 1,000 years old."},{"time":682000,"text":"There are four humans in this shot -- one, two, three, four."},{"time":690000,"text":"And there's also something that I want to show you."},{"time":693000,"text":"This is a flying buttress."},{"time":696000,"text":"Redwoods grow back into themselves as they expand into space,"},{"time":700000,"text":"and this flying buttress is a limb shot out of that small trunk,"},{"time":703000,"text":"going back into the main trunk and fusing with it."},{"time":706000,"text":"Flying buttresses, just as in a cathedral, help strengthen the crown of the tree"},{"time":710000,"text":"and help the tree exist longer through time."},{"time":714000,"text":"The scientists are doing all kinds of experiments in these trees."},{"time":718000,"text":"They've wired them like patients in an ICU."}]},{"cues":[{"time":721000,"text":"They're finding out that Redwoods can move moisture out of the air"},{"time":724000,"text":"and down into their trunks,"},{"time":726000,"text":"possibly all the way into their root systems."},{"time":728000,"text":"They also have the ability to put roots anywhere in the tree itself."},{"time":732000,"text":"If a portion of a Redwood is rotting,"},{"time":734000,"text":"the Redwood will send roots into its own form"},{"time":737000,"text":"and draw nutrients out of itself as it falls apart."},{"time":741000,"text":"If we had Redwood-like biology, if we got a touch of gangrene in our arm"},{"time":745000,"text":"then we could just, you know,"},{"time":747000,"text":"extract the nutrients extract the nutrients and the moisture out of it until it fell off."},{"time":752000,"text":"Canopy soil can occur up to a meter deep,"},{"time":755000,"text":"hundreds of feet above the ground, and there are organisms in this soil"},{"time":759000,"text":"that have, as yet, no names."}]},{"cues":[{"time":761000,"text":"This is an unnamed species of copepod. A copepod is a crustacean."},{"time":766000,"text":"These copepods are a major constituent of the oceans,"},{"time":771000,"text":"and they are a major part of the diet of grazing baleen whales."},{"time":775000,"text":"What they're doing in the Redwood forest canopy soil"},{"time":779000,"text":"hundreds of feet above the ocean, or how they got there,"},{"time":782000,"text":"is completely unknown."},{"time":784000,"text":"There are some interesting theories"},{"time":786000,"text":"that, if I had time, I would tell you about."},{"time":788000,"text":"But as you go and you look closer at a tree,"},{"time":790000,"text":"what you see is, you see increasing complexity."},{"time":793000,"text":"We're looking at the very top of Gaya, which is thought to be the oldest Redwood."},{"time":797000,"text":"Gaya may be 3,000 to 5,000 years old,"},{"time":802000,"text":"no one really knows, but its top has broken off"},{"time":805000,"text":"and it's been rotting back now."}]},{"cues":[{"time":807000,"text":"This little Japanese garden-like creation probably took 700 years"},{"time":813000,"text":"to form in its complexity that we see right now."},{"time":817000,"text":"As you look at a tree, it takes a magnifying glass to see a giant tree."},{"time":822000,"text":"I have to show you something unfortunately very sad"},{"time":825000,"text":"at the conclusion of this talk."},{"time":827000,"text":"The Eastern Hemlock tree has often been described as the Redwood of the East."},{"time":831000,"text":"And we're moving in a full circle now."},{"time":833000,"text":"In the 1950s, a small organism appeared in Richmond, Virginia,"},{"time":838000,"text":"called the Hemlock woolly adelgid."},{"time":840000,"text":"It made a trans-species jump out of some other organism in Asia,"},{"time":844000,"text":"where it was living on Hemlock trees in Asia."},{"time":847000,"text":"When it moved into its new host, the Eastern Hemlock tree,"},{"time":851000,"text":"it escaped its predators, and the new tree had no resistance to it."},{"time":855000,"text":"The Eastern Hemlock forest is being considered in some ways"},{"time":859000,"text":"the last fragments of primeval rainforest east of the Mississippi River."}]},{"cues":[{"time":864000,"text":"I hadn't even known that there were rainforests in the east,"},{"time":867000,"text":"but in Great Smoky Mountains National Park"},{"time":870000,"text":"it can rain up to 100 inches of rain a year."},{"time":875000,"text":"And in the last two to three summers, these invasive organisms,"},{"time":882000,"text":"this kind of Ebola of the trees, as it were,"},{"time":885000,"text":"has swept through the primeval Hemlock forest of the east,"},{"time":889000,"text":"and has absolutely wiped it out. I climbed there this past summer."},{"time":894000,"text":"This is Great Smoky Mountains National Park,"},{"time":896000,"text":"and the Hemlocks are dead as far as the eye can see."},{"time":901000,"text":"And what we're seeing is not just the potential death"},{"time":904000,"text":"of the Eastern Hemlock species --"},{"time":907000,"text":"that is to say, its extinction from nature due to this invading parasite --"},{"time":911000,"text":"but we're also seeing the death of an incredibly complex ecosystem"},{"time":916000,"text":"for which these trees are merely the substrate"},{"time":919000,"text":"for the aerial labyrinth of the sky that exists in their crowns."}]},{"cues":[{"time":925000,"text":"It's absolutely heartbreaking to see."},{"time":928000,"text":"One of the things that is just -- I almost can't conceive it --"},{"time":932000,"text":"is the idea that the national news media hasn't picked this up at all,"},{"time":936000,"text":"and this is the devastation of one of the most important ecosystems in North America."},{"time":944000,"text":"What can the Redwoods tell us about ourselves?"},{"time":947000,"text":"Well, I think they can tell us something about human time."},{"time":950000,"text":"The flickering, transitory quality of human time"},{"time":955000,"text":"and the brevity of human life -- the necessity to love."},{"time":960000,"text":"But we're different from trees, and they can also teach us"},{"time":962000,"text":"something about ourselves in the differences that we have."},{"time":965000,"text":"We are human, and we have the capacity to love,"},{"time":968000,"text":"we have the capacity to wonder, and we have a sort of"},{"time":972000,"text":"boundless curiosity, a restless inquisitiveness"},{"time":977000,"text":"that so suits us as primates, I think."}]},{"cues":[{"time":980000,"text":"And at least for me, personally, the trees have taught me"},{"time":984000,"text":"an entirely new way of loving my children."},{"time":987000,"text":"Exploring with them the forest canopy"},{"time":989000,"text":"has been one of the most lovely things of my existence on Earth."},{"time":993000,"text":"And I think that one of the happiest things is the sense that"},{"time":998000,"text":"with my children I've been able to introduce them"},{"time":1001000,"text":"into the very small circle of humans who are lucky enough,"},{"time":1005000,"text":"or possibly stupid enough, to still climb trees."},{"time":1009000,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1011000,"text":"(Applause)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1022000,"text":"Chris Anderson: I think at a previous TED,"},{"time":1025000,"text":"I think it was Nathan Myhrvold who told me that it was thought that"},{"time":1029000,"text":"because these trees are like, 2,000 years and older,"},{"time":1032000,"text":"on many of them there are ecosystems where there are species"},{"time":1035000,"text":"that are not found anywhere on the Earth"},{"time":1037000,"text":"except on that one tree. Is that correct?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1040000,"text":"Richard Preston: Yes, that is correct. I mentioned Hyperion, the world's tallest tree."},{"time":1045000,"text":"And I was a member of a climbing team that made the first climb of it, in 2006."},{"time":1050000,"text":"And while we were climbing Hyperion, Marie Antoine spotted"},{"time":1054000,"text":"an unknown species of golden-brown ant about halfway up the trunk."},{"time":1060000,"text":"Ants are not known to occur in Redwood trees, curiously enough,"},{"time":1063000,"text":"and we wondered whether this ant, this species of ant,"},{"time":1066000,"text":"was only endemic to that one tree, or possibly to that grove."},{"time":1070000,"text":"And in subsequent climbs they could never find that ant again,"},{"time":1073000,"text":"and so no specimens have ever been collected."},{"time":1075000,"text":"We don't know what it is -- we just know it's there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1079000,"text":"CA: So, you have to wonder when, you know,"},{"time":1081000,"text":"if some other species than us was recording the stories that mattered on Earth,"},{"time":1087000,"text":"you know, our stories are about Iraq and war and politics and celebrity gossip."},{"time":1093000,"text":"You've just told us a different story of this tragic arms race that's happening,"},{"time":1097000,"text":"and maybe whole ecosystems gone forever."},{"time":1100000,"text":"It's an amazing sense of wonder you've given me,"},{"time":1102000,"text":"and a sense of just how fragile this whole thing is."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1105000,"text":"RP: It is fragile, and you know, I think about emerging human diseases --"},{"time":1109000,"text":"parasites that move into the human species."},{"time":1112000,"text":"But that's just a very small facet"},{"time":1115000,"text":"of a much greater problem of invasions of species worldwide,"},{"time":1119000,"text":"all through the ecosystems, and you know, the Earth itself --"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1121000,"text":"CA: Partly caused by us, inadvertently."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1124000,"text":"RP: Caused by humans. Caused by the movement of humans."},{"time":1127000,"text":"You can think of the Earth's biosphere as a palace,"},{"time":1132000,"text":"and the continents are rooms in the palace,"},{"time":1135000,"text":"and the islands are small rooms."},{"time":1137000,"text":"But lately, the doors of the palace have been flung open,"},{"time":1141000,"text":"and the walls are coming down."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1144000,"text":"CA: Richard Preston, thank you very much, I think."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1146000,"text":"RP: Thank you."}]}]}